answers.body_markdown:
&gt;So, my question is: **what&#39;s the significance of including the word `.prototype` in `Array.prototype.includes()` in the documentation, when the actual usage looks like: `Array.includes()`?**

The significance is that actual usage *doesn&#39;t* look like `Array.includes()`:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    Array.includes();
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

That will throw a [`TypeError: Array.includes is not a function`](https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-standard-typeerror) because `Array.includes` [*doesn&#39;t exist*](https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-array-objects). Accessing a non-existing property [evaluates to `undefined`](https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-property-accessors-runtime-semantics-evaluation), so `Array.includes` evaluates to `undefined` and thus `Array.includes()` is trying to call `undefined` as if were a function.

You can see that in action here:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    console.log(Array.includes);

    undefined();
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

[The `includes()` method is defined on the *prototype* of the `Array` global object](https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-array.prototype.includes) so that you can call it on *instances* of `Array`:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    [].includes();
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You can see that `[].includes` is a function:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    console.log([].includes);
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Compare this to [`Array.from`](https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-array.from) which is defined on the *`Array` constructor*, not on the *`Array` prototype*:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    console.log(Array.from);
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You can use it like this:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    console.log(Array.from({ length: 10 }, (_, num) =&gt; num &lt;&lt; 2));
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

If the documentation said `Array.includes()` you would literally type it like this (example):
```javascript
Array.includes(1);
```
Instead it says `Array.prototype.includes()` which means it isn&#39;t called on the `Array` type itself, but on an instance of it. So in this case you would write:
```javascript
const numbers = [1, 2, 3];
numbers.includes(1);
```

