You&#39;ve to bind each texture object to a different texture unit. The texture unit can be chosen by [`glActiveTexture`](https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/es3.0/html/glActiveTexture.xhtml).

This means if you&#39;ve 3 texture objects `t1`, `t2` and `t3`, then you&#39;ve to set the current texture unit before you bind the texture object to the target by [`glBindTexture`](https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/es3.0/html/glBindTexture.xhtml):

```lang-none
GLES20.glActiveTexture(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE0);
GLES20.glBindTexture(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE_2D, t1);
GLES20.glActiveTexture(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE1);
GLES20.glBindTexture(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE_2D, t2);
GLES20.glActiveTexture(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE2);
GLES20.glBindTexture(GLES20.GL_TEXTURE_2D, t3);
```

The number of the texture unit has to be set to the texture sampler uniform. The number of the uniform is the binding point of the texture object and the sampler uniform. 
 
Get the resource (location) index of the uniform by [`glGetUniformLocation`](https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/es3.0/html/glGetUniformLocation.xhtml) and set the binding point by [`glUniform1i`](https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/es3.0/html/glUniform.xhtml). e.g.:

```lang-none
int loc_t1 = GLES20.glGetUniformLocation(program, &quot;inputImageTexture&quot;);
int loc_t2 = GLES20.glGetUniformLocation(program, &quot;inputImageTexture2&quot;);
int loc_t3 = GLES20.glGetUniformLocation(program, &quot;inputImageTexture3&quot;);
```

`program` is the shader program object.

```lang-none
GLES20.glUniform1i(loc_t1, 0);
GLES20.glUniform1i(loc_t2, 1);
GLES20.glUniform1i(loc_t3, 2); 
```

0, 1 and 2 are the binding points, which are the numbers of the texture units `GL_TEXTURE0`, `GL_TEXTURE1` and `GL_TEXTURE2`.

