I think you misunderstood how `ViewSets` work. A single `ViewSet` could contain the whole logic you wish for your model. I think there is a collision here when you register the routes which makes one of the `ViewSet` inoperative.

You should merge all your logic in a single `ViewSet`:

```py
class UserViewSet(
    mixins.CreateModelMixin,
    mixins.ListModelMixin,
    mixins.RetrieveModelMixin,
    mixins.UpdateModelMixin,
    mixins.DestroyModelMixin,
    viewsets.GenericViewSet,
):
    queryset = User.objects.all()
    permission_classes = (AllowAny,)

    def get_serializer_class(self):
        &quot;&quot;&quot;Return the serializer class given the action&quot;&quot;&quot;
        action = self.action
        if self.action == &#39;create&#39; or self.action == &#39;list&#39;:
            return CreateUserSerializer
        else:
            return UserSerializer

    def list(self, request, *args, **kwargs):
        email = self.request.query_params.get(&#39;email&#39;, None)
        phone_no = self.request.query_params.get(&#39;phone_no&#39;, None)

        if email is not None:
            queryset = User.objects.filter(email=email)
        elif phone_no is not None:
            queryset = User.objects.filter(phone_no=phone_no)
        else:
            queryset = User.objects.all()
        return super().list(request, *args, **kwargs)
```

A few comments about my example:

* I overrided `get_serializer_class` because I saw you had two different serializers on your viewsets. However, I&#39;m quite sure you can do what you want by using [`read_only`/`write_only` options](https://www.django-rest-framework.org/api-guide/fields/#core-arguments) of the `Serializer` fields.
* In your `list` view, you are implementing some filtering logic. You can do this more easily with [`django-filter`](https://www.django-rest-framework.org/api-guide/filtering/#djangofilterbackend), without having to overload the `list` method.

